ic as the decade began, Republicans eagerly exploited alternative media opportunities. Using the stereopticon (a modernized magic lantern), they developed the first campaign documentaries. Soon they were exploiting motion pictures, the phonograph, and telephone in surprising and often successful ways. Brimming with rich historical details, Musser's remarkable tale reveals the political forces driving the emergence of modern media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPolitical campaignsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPolitical campaignszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPresidentsxElectionsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxElectionxHistoryy19th century. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxElectionsxHistoryy19th century. 0aPress and politicsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPress and politicszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016z978311066754708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966123423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520966123.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066754-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles